    "front": "Distinguish inclusive ('soft') positivism from exclusive ('hard') positivism.",
    "back": "Inclusive positivism (Hart's Postscript, Waluchow, Coleman): the rule of recognition CAN include moral criteria for legal validity — e.g. a constitution may make fundamental rights part of the test for valid law. Morality is not necessarily relevant but can be made relevant by social convention. Exclusive positivism (Raz): the existence and content of law depends ONLY on social facts, never on moral criteria. Moral tests cannot be part of the rule of recognition because law must be identifiable without moral deliberation.",
    "details": "Raz's argument: law claims authority, and authority requires that directives be identifiable without engaging in the very deliberation the authority is meant to pre-empt. If identifying law requires moral reasoning, law cannot serve its mediating function. Hart's Postscript (published posthumously, 1994) aligned with inclusive positivism. This debate is internal to positivism — both sides agree law and morality are conceptually distinct; they disagree about whether moral tests can feature in the rule of recognition.",
