    "details": "Hobbes's sovereign can be a monarch or assembly but must have absolute, undivided authority — any limitation leads back to the state of nature. Unlike later social contract theorists (Locke, Rousseau), Hobbes's sovereign is not bound by the contract and cannot be removed. The sovereign's laws create obligations — without a sovereign, there is no right or wrong. Hobbes is often considered a precursor of legal positivism because he separates the question of what law IS from natural law morality.",
