    "front": "What is Dworkin's 'chain novel' analogy and how does it illustrate law as integrity?",
    "back": "In Law's Empire (1986), Dworkin compares legal interpretation to writing a chain novel: each judge is like an author who must continue a story already begun by others. They must interpret existing chapters (past decisions and legislation) and write a new chapter that both 'fits' the story so far and makes it the best story it can be. Similarly, a judge must find the interpretation of law that best fits existing legal materials and presents them in their best moral light — this is 'law as integrity.'",
    "details": "Dworkin distinguished three conceptions of law: (1) conventionalism (law is what conventions/past decisions say — close to positivism); (2) pragmatism (judges should decide cases to produce the best consequences, unconstrained by the past); (3) law as integrity (judges must treat the law as a coherent, principled whole). Integrity requires both 'fit' (consistency with past decisions) and 'justification' (the best moral reading). The ideal judge 'Hercules' has superhuman learning and patience to construct the theory that best satisfies both dimensions. Critics argue this is unrealistic and that reasonable judges will disagree about the 'best' interpretation.",
