    "back": "CRT (Delgado, Crenshaw, Bell) holds that: (1) racism is not aberrational but ordinary — embedded in legal structures and institutions; (2) formal equality (treating everyone the same) fails to address structural disadvantage; (3) race is a social construct, not biological, but has real material consequences; (4) the experiences and voices of people of colour must be centred (counter-storytelling). Kimberlé Crenshaw's concept of 'intersectionality' shows that race, gender, class, and other categories interact to produce compound forms of disadvantage that single-axis analysis cannot capture.",
    "details": "CRT emerged from CLS in the late 1980s — sharing the CLS critique of law's neutrality but focusing specifically on race. Derrick Bell's 'interest convergence' thesis: advances in racial justice occur only when they also serve white interests (e.g. Brown v Board of Education served Cold War diplomacy interests). CRT critiques 'colour-blindness' as perpetuating inequality by ignoring structural racism. Intersectionality (Crenshaw, 1989): a Black woman's experience of discrimination is not simply racism plus sexism — the intersection creates distinct and compounded disadvantage that neither category alone describes. CRT has influenced UK race equality law scholarship.",
