    "front": "What is Mill's harm principle and how does it define the limits of legitimate legal interference?",
    "back": "John Stuart Mill (On Liberty, 1859): 'the only purpose for which power can be rightfully exercised over any member of a civilised community, against his will, is to prevent harm to others.' Self-regarding conduct — actions that affect only the individual — cannot be legitimately restricted by law. Paternalism (restricting liberty for the person's own good) and legal moralism (criminalising conduct solely because it is immoral) are both illegitimate grounds for state coercion.",
    "details": "Mill's principle underpins the liberal theory of criminal law — the state should only criminalise conduct that harms others. The Hart-Devlin debate (1960s) tested this: Lord Devlin argued society has a right to enforce its shared morality through law (legal moralism — the 'fabric of society' argument). Hart (following Mill) argued that the mere fact that conduct is immoral is insufficient to justify criminalisation. The Wolfenden Report (1957) on homosexuality reflected Mill's position. Feinberg extended the harm principle to include 'offence' as a potential ground for restriction. Critics: the definition of 'harm' is contested and potentially infinitely expandable.",
