    "back": "Literal/textualist approach: the court applies the ordinary meaning of the words used — reflects positivism (law is what the legislature enacted, not what it should have said). Purposive approach: the court identifies the purpose or mischief the statute was intended to address and interprets accordingly — reflects Fuller's view that law has purpose and judges must give effect to it. The mischief rule (Heydon's Case (1584)) and Pepper v Hart [1993] (consulting Hansard) reflect purposive reasoning.",
