    "front": "Distinguish the 'will' (choice) theory and the 'interest' (benefit) theory of rights.",
    "back": "Will theory (Hart): a right is a protected choice — the right-holder has the power to enforce or waive the correlative duty. Rights exist to protect individual autonomy. Interest theory (Raz, MacCormick): a right exists when an interest of the right-holder is sufficient to ground a duty on another. Rights protect important interests, not choices. The theories produce different results: will theory cannot explain rights of children or incompetent persons (who cannot exercise choice); interest theory can, but may be over-inclusive.",
    "details": "Hohfeld (Fundamental Legal Conceptions, 1919) provided the foundational analytical framework: (1) claim-right (correlative: duty); (2) liberty/privilege (correlative: no-right); (3) power (correlative: liability); (4) immunity (correlative: disability). Every legal relation can be analysed into these building blocks. Hohfeld showed that 'a right' is ambiguous — it may refer to any of these four relations. Modern rights discourse often conflates different Hohfeldian incidents. Raz's interest theory links rights to the justification of duties: X has a right if X's interest is sufficient reason to hold another under a duty.",
