    "front": "What is Rousseau's concept of the 'general will'?",
    "back": "Jean-Jacques Rousseau (The Social Contract, 1762): legitimate political authority rests on a social contract in which individuals surrender their natural liberty to the community and in return receive civil liberty and equality. The sovereign power lies in the 'general will' (volonté générale) — the common good of the whole community, as opposed to the 'will of all' (mere aggregation of private interests). Law is legitimate only when it expresses the general will. Obedience to the general will is 'freedom' because it represents what rational citizens would choose for the common good.",
    "details": "Rousseau's famous paradox: a person who disobeys the general will may be 'forced to be free' — because the general will represents their true rational interests as a citizen. Critics: this is dangerously authoritarian — it can justify coercion in the name of 'real' freedom (Berlin's 'positive liberty' critique). Rousseau differed from Hobbes (sovereignty is absolute but held by the people, not a monarch) and Locke (Rousseau's emphasis on equality and the general will goes beyond Locke's natural rights framework). Rousseau influenced the French Revolution, republican theory, and participatory democracy. His ideas resonate in debates about direct democracy and citizen participation.",
