    "back": "Postmodern jurisprudence challenges the Enlightenment assumptions underlying both positivism and natural law — that law is rational, coherent, and determinate. Key influences: Derrida's 'deconstruction' reveals instabilities and contradictions in legal texts — legal meaning is never fixed but always deferred. Foucault's analysis of power/knowledge shows that law is not a neutral framework but a mechanism of disciplinary power that produces and controls subjects. Lyotard's 'incredulity toward metanarratives' questions whether any grand theory of law (positivist, natural law, or Marxist) can provide a complete account.",
