    "front": "What is the 'law and economics' approach to legal theory?",
    "back": "Law and economics (Posner, Calabresi, Coase) analyses legal rules in terms of their economic efficiency. Richard Posner (Economic Analysis of Law, 1973) argued that the common law tends toward efficiency — legal rules should (and do) allocate resources to their highest-valued use. The Coase Theorem (1960): where transaction costs are zero, the initial allocation of legal rights does not affect the efficient outcome — parties will bargain to the optimal result regardless. When transaction costs are positive, legal rules should mimic the outcome the parties would have reached through costless bargaining.",
    "details": "Applications: tort law as efficient deterrence (Learned Hand formula: negligence where B < PL — the cost of precaution is less than the probability of harm times the magnitude of loss); contract law as facilitating efficient breach (breach is efficient if the cost of performance exceeds its value to the promisee); property law as minimising the 'tragedy of the commons.' Criticisms: (1) reduces justice to efficiency — ignores distributional concerns and rights (Dworkin); (2) wealth maximisation is not a moral value (Rawls, Sen); (3) the Coase Theorem's assumptions (zero transaction costs, perfect information) rarely hold. Despite criticisms, law and economics has profoundly influenced US legal scholarship and policy.",
